<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="39">
1. Subgenus 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146889" authority="Weber, 1938" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomannia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomannia Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cyphomannia</taxonomicName>
Weber -
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="40" pageNumber="39">
This optional category was founded upon the lone Bolivian species 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28530" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex laevigatus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevigatus">laevigatus Weber</taxonomicName>
. It is indeed a striking species. The completely smooth thorax, devoid of the costumary tubercles, teeth and spines is unique. Nevertheless, the overall appearance and a set of characters which to my mind are useful for infrageneric grouping (without going into subgenera) show that 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28530" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex laevigatus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevigatus">laevigatus</taxonomicName>
falls nicely into the rimosus-group, in a stricter sense, i. e. excluding the somewhat aberrant forms such as 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28533" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex longiscapus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiscapus">longiscapus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28522" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex costatus Mann" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">costatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28551" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex wheeleri Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wheeleri">wheeleri</taxonomicName>
and possible allies. The head of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28530" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex laevigatus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevigatus">laevigatus</taxonomicName>
is practically identical with that of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28517" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex bicornis Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicornis">bicornis</taxonomicName>
, and the latter also lacks a pronotal and epinotal armature, only the mesonotum having an anterior pair of conical low spines and a posterior pair of inconspicuous welts; in addition, the petiole and postpetiole of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28517" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex bicornis Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicornis">bicornis</taxonomicName>
are practically smooth as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28530" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex laevigatus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevigatus">laevigatus</taxonomicName>
(cf. Kempf, 1966: 177-9, figs. 4, 5, 23, 26, 32, 33). Moreover, Weber is wrong in assuming that when I first proposed this case of synonymy (Kempf, 1962) I had no direct knowledge of laevigatus-material. Already in 1961 (p. 518) I mentioned the specimens from Dutch Guiana which are perfectly identical with the types, available to me already by the end of 1962. Since 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2389" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cyphomyrmex</taxonomicName>
contains other striking and morphologically isolated species (v. gr. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28539" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex occultus Kempf" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occultus">occultus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28536" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex morschi Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morschi">morschi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28533" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomyrmex longiscapus Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiscapus">longiscapus</taxonomicName>
), there would be no end for decorative subgenera. Therefore, I consider 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:146889" authority="Weber, 1938" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cyphomannia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Cyphomannia Weber" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cyphomannia</taxonomicName>
a useless burden which should stay buried for the sake of healthy taxonomy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
